You can set a role hierarchy by exposing a `RoleHierarchy` bean.
```
@Bean
public RoleHierarchy roleHierarchy() {
	RoleHierarchyImpl roleHierarchy = new RoleHierarchyImpl();
	roleHierarchy.setHierarchy(&quot;ROLE_ADMIN &gt; ROLE_ONE\nROLE_A &gt; ROLE_TWO\nROLE_B &gt; ROLE_TWO\nROLE_C &gt; ROLE_TWO&quot;);
	return roleHierarchy;
}
```
This is saying that if a user is `&quot;ROLE_ADMIN&quot;` then they are also `&quot;ROLE_ONE&quot;`.  
If a user is `&quot;ROLE_A&quot;` then they are also `&quot;ROLE_TWO&quot;`.  
If a user is `&quot;ROLE_B&quot;` then they are also `&quot;ROLE_TWO&quot;`.  
If a user is `&quot;ROLE_C&quot;` then they are also `&quot;ROLE_TWO&quot;`.  
You can define multiple role hierarchies by using a newline `\n` to separate them.

